5:
Good morning, Eduardo. You're up
early. Doing some studying?
9:
The curse of the depths? I see. It's a
shame your research hasn't yielded
any results thus far.
14:
Indeed. I've pored over every history
book I could find, but there were no
incidents similar to mine.
21:
Eduardo, do you mind me asking
when you got that power?
25:
Long ago, as I was drowning at the
bottom of the sea.
29:
The vessel I was on was destroyed,
and I was sent to a watery grave,
sinking ever downwards.
32:
Just then, in the deepest, darkest
depths of the sea, I encountered it.
Something utterly indescribable...
35:
When I next woke, I was lying in an
infirmary.
37:
By that point, the curse had already
overtaken my body.
40:
What was this... thing you
encountered?
46:
I can't remember. Even before I lost
consciousness, my vision was blurry
at best.
49:
All I know is that every time I use my
power, I get visions of this particular
mark here.
54:
What are you all doing in the library
at the crack of dawn?
Huh, that...
66:
Yeah. I have.
Someone I once knew had
something with a similar mark.
68:
But that was a long time ago. 
And I can't even say for sure that 
they're the same.
73:
I don't care. Please tell me where
you saw it!
79:
...There's no end in sight. How far do
these sands stretch on?
81:
So this is a desert... I'd read about
them, but to see one for yourself is
something else.
85:
What're you just standing around
for? Did you forget why you came
here?
88:
The one Rolan had was a relic from
an ancient civilization.
90:
There's a merchant who sells stolen
artifacts up this way. I'm thinking
that's our best chance at finding it.
95:
I understand. Can you guide me
there?
100:
I hope it's the one you're looking for,
Eduardo.
104:
There is a mark engraved in this
one. What do you think, Eduardo?
Does this match the one you saw?
108:
It bears a resemblance...
This geometric pattern... It means
"gate."
111:
So the mark exists on different
worlds... This has quite the
fascinating implications.
115:
Still, though similar, it is undoubtedly
a different mark entirely. Sorry to
make you go through all this trouble.
118:
Meh. You win some, you lose some.
Don't sweat it.
122:
...Thank you.
But I'd be lying if I said it didn't sting.
136:
You suddenly passed out, that's
what. Probably from exhaustion.
Have you been sleeping at all?
141:
Ah, I see...
I'm sorry to worry you like that.
145:
Alk and the rest went off to buy
some stuff in town.
149:
And you didn't go with them? 
I thought this was your home.
152:
Eh, there's not much to see. Mostly
sand. It's also not even really my
home.
155:
I ended up in this world when I was a
kid. Got stranded in the desert.
160:
I suppose that makes you a drifter,
then.
162:
Interesting to see that the
phenomenon exists in other worlds
as well...
164:
If that's the case, then the possibility
that my powers came from another
world is quite high...
167:
Pardon me.
I have a lot on my mind.
171:
No problem. I'm used to dealing with
people who think too much.
176:
I just... I can't stand the idea that I'm
being manipulated or controlled by
something I don't understand...
178:
I have to find out what it is. To do so,
I need to amass more
knowledgeno matter what it takes.
Do you disapprove of my methods?
181:
I never said that. I mean, do I think
you're kind of weird? Sure.
184:
Still, I can understand that. Not
knowing pisses you off, so that
drives you forward. Reminds me of
someone I know.
187:
Those guys are running late. 
Maybe I should go meet up with 'em.
190:
What are you gonna do? Wait here
patiently till we go home?
195:
No. I'll go with you. Investigating is
what I do best, after all.
